tizo_trico wrote:
&gt; St.Ack,
&gt;
&gt; Yes, Yan Zhang&#39;s suggestion works; I already have been working in that
&gt; way, but I wonderer  if that could be done automatically.

What would you suggest?
&gt;
&gt; I have also thought in make a Java program that controls Heritrix via
&gt; JMX, and creates jobs &quot;based on existing jobs&quot;, as soon as they
&gt; finished, but what about the seeds?, how can I recover the same seeds?
I may be misinterpreting your question.  Are you asking how to reuse the 
same seeds in every job?  If so, as part of creating a job, you specify 
the seeds to use usually by having the order.xml point to a seeds.txt 
file, the very file that was used in all previous crawls.  With JMX you 
can pass paths to the order and seed file to use or pass seeds as a 
string or pass a jar file that has the order and seeds as well as any 
settings overrides (The latter makes it easier posting jobs to a remote 
Heritrix instance).
&gt; Should the program itself control the seeds for each &quot;reusable&quot; job?
&gt; or there is a simpler way?
&gt;
&gt; Anyway, when you say &quot;Automated rescheduling of jobs is not part of
&gt; the crawler.&quot;, is because it should not be part of the crawler? 
Thats what I think.  Keeps things modular and our options open.  
Scheduler can then be as simple as a cron job invoking heritrix 
command-line arguments or as sophisticated as quartz 
(http://www.opensymphony.com/quartz/) invoking Heritrix via JMX as 
originally suggested up on this list a while back 
(http://groups.yahoo.com/group/archive-crawler/message/1827).

&gt; or
&gt; could it be a new functionality for future releases? It the last was
&gt; true, maybe I could work on that, but I don&#39;t know yet, because we are
&gt; studying the best way to implement the reusability of jobs, and one of
&gt; the alternatives is modifying Heritrix code.
For sure it could be part of a future Heritrix and we&#39;d welcome any 
scheduling contribution.

For our archive-it service we have a basic scheduler that lets you start 
a job at defined coarse intervals (Once a day, once a week, etc.).  This 
&#39;scheduling&#39; is built into the application that manages all of the 
Hertrice instances each running distinct crawl jobs.  It does this via 
the hcc Heritrix subproject: http://crawler.archive.org/hcc/ (hcc is 
beginnings of a &#39;Heritrix Cluster Controller&#39;, an application that can 
give a view onto a cluster of Heritrix crawlers).  If hcc had a built-in 
scheduler, our archive-it would likely use it. If it was part of hcc, so 
could others.

Myself, I don&#39;t see much value in adding a scheduler to Heritrix itself: 
Another heavy jar, multiple specification screens if the scheduler is of 
any sophistication at all, and a new place on disk to worry about  for 
persisted schedules.  I&#39;d be more interested in an external scheduler 
that is able to schedule multiple instances being part of a separate 
cluster-management application but perhaps others see value in building 
scheduling into Heritrix itself?

St.Ack

